\begin_layout Chapter
Grading the PML
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Chapter 1, we have seen that the general expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}$
\end_inset

 in TEz mode is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{z}=H_{0}\cdot e^{i\omega t}\cdot e^{i(-\sqrt{s_{x}s_{m,x}}k_{x}\cdot x)}\cdot e^{i(-\sqrt{s_{y}s_{m,y}}k_{y}\cdot y)}
\]

\end_inset

by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "general_Hz"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And we also have demonstrated the conditions for zero-reflection are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{x}=s_{m,x}\qquad s_{y}=s_{m,y}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus final form is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{2}=H_{t,z}=\hat{z}\mathscr{T}H_{0}e^{i\omega t}e^{i(-k_{1,y}y)}e^{i(-k_{1,x}x)}e^{-\sigma_{x}\cdot x\cdot\eta_{1}\cos\theta}\ref{H2 attenuation factor}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's focus on the attenuation factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\sigma_{x}\cdot x\cdot\eta_{1}\cos\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 In practice, wave incident to PML region, reaches at PEC boundary at the
 end then reflected to PML boundary.
 So, in essence, the wave will have attenuated by a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\sigma_{x}\cdot2thick_{pml}\cdot\eta_{1}\cos\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 Then in general, we define the reflection factor 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta)$
\end_inset

 as,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R(\theta)=\exp(-2\eta\cos\theta\cdot\int_{0}^{d}\sigma_{x}(x)dx)\label{Reflection factor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In FDTD method, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}$
\end_inset

 are interleaved by a half of spatial step, they enter PML region differently.
 To reduce reflection error caused by the inborn feature, Berenger proposed
 the grading of PML region.
 The proposed profile of conductivity is given by,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{x} & =\left(\frac{x}{d}\right)^{m}\sigma_{x,max}\label{graded sigma}\\
\kappa_{x}(x) & =1+(\kappa_{x,max}-1)\cdot\left(\frac{x}{d}\right)^{m}\label{graded kappa}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 denotes thickness of PML.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}$
\end_inset

 is usually unity.
 Applying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "graded sigma"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Reflection factor"

\end_inset

, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R(\theta)=e^{-2\eta\sigma_{x,max}d\cdot\cos\theta/(m+1)}\label{reflection factor sigma max}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is known by many reseachs that 10 cells of PML works fine in most simulation,
 in which case the thickness is 
\begin_inset Formula $10\cdot dx$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $3\leq m\leq4$
\end_inset

 is found to be optimal for most case.
 The maximum conductivity is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{x,max}=-\frac{(m+1)ln(R(0))}{2\eta d}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $R(0)$
\end_inset

 is the disired reflection at normal incidence; this is typically taken
 to be on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-6}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Convolutional PML
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Convolutional PML(CPML) method is the most recently developed method.
 This theory has derived by Roden and Gedney in 2000.
 It includes the methodology to absorbs evanescent wave, which was impossible
 in previous two methodology, UPML and Split-field method.
 It has more accuracy and efficiency than previous methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stretched coordinate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before discussion of CPML theory, we should understand stretched coordinate
 representation.
 Consider isotropic PML region of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ampere's law and Faraday's law yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{x}}{\partial t}+\sigma\mathscr{E}_{x} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}-\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial z}\\
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{y}}{\partial t}+\sigma\mathscr{E}_{y} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial z}-\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial x}\\
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{z}}{\partial t}+\sigma\mathscr{E}_{z} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial x}-\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial y}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial t}+\sigma^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{x} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{y}}{\partial z}-\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{z}}{\partial y}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial t}+\sigma^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{y} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{z}}{\partial x}-\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{x}}{\partial z}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial t}+\sigma^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{z} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{x}}{\partial y}-\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{y}}{\partial x}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By split field methods,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{xy}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{y}\mathscr{E}_{xy} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}\\
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{xz}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{z}\mathscr{E}_{xz} & =-\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial z}\\
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{yz}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{z}\mathscr{E}_{yz} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial z}\\
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{yx}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{x}\mathscr{E}_{yx} & =-\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial x}\\
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{zx}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{x}\mathscr{E}_{zx} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial x}\\
\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{zy}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{y}\mathscr{E}_{zy} & =-\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial y}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{xy}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{y}^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{xy} & =-\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{z}}{\partial y}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{xz}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{z}^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{xz} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{y}}{\partial z}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{yx}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{x}^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{yx} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{z}}{\partial x}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{yz}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{z}^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{yz} & =-\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{x}}{\partial z}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{zx}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{x}^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{zx} & =-\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{y}}{\partial x}\\
\mu_{0}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{zy}}{\partial t}+\sigma_{y}^{\ast}\mathscr{H}_{zy} & =\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{x}}{\partial y}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 In frequency domain, the first two equation becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(i\omega\epsilon_{0}+\sigma_{y}\right)\mathscr{E}_{xy} & =i\omega\epsilon_{0}s_{y}\mathscr{E}_{xy}=\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}\quad\rightarrow\quad i\omega\epsilon_{0}\mathscr{E}_{xy}=\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}\\
\left(i\omega\epsilon_{0}+\sigma_{z}\right)\mathscr{E}_{xz} & =i\omega\epsilon_{0}s_{z}\mathscr{E}_{xz}=-\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial z}\quad\rightarrow\quad i\omega\epsilon_{0}\mathscr{E}_{xz}=-\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial z}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding two equations yields,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\omega\epsilon_{0}\mathscr{E}_{x}=\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}-\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial z}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the same token, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
i\omega\epsilon_{0}\mathscr{E}_{x} & =\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}-\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial z}\\
i\omega\epsilon_{0}\mathscr{E}_{y} & =\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial z}-\frac{1}{s_{x}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial x}\\
i\omega\epsilon_{0}\mathscr{E}_{z} & =\frac{1}{s_{x}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial x}-\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial y}\\
i\omega\mu_{0}\mathscr{H}_{x} & =\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{y}}{\partial z}-\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{z}}{\partial y}\\
i\omega\mu_{0}\mathscr{H}_{y} & =\frac{1}{s_{x}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{z}}{\partial x}-\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{x}}{\partial z}\\
i\omega\mu_{0}\mathscr{H}_{z} & =\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{x}}{\partial y}-\frac{1}{s_{x}}\frac{\partial\mathscr{E}_{y}}{\partial x}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
3D PML region
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ampere's law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Ampere's law in frequency domain becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overrightarrow{\nabla}\times\overrightarrow{H}=i\omega\overrightarrow{D}+\overrightarrow{J}=i\omega\epsilon\overrightarrow{E}+\sigma\overrightarrow{E}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial y}-\frac{\partial H_{y}}{\partial z}\\
\frac{\partial H_{x}}{\partial z}-\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial x}\\
\frac{\partial H_{y}}{\partial x}-\frac{\partial H_{x}}{\partial y}
\end{matrix}\right]=(i\omega\epsilon_{0}+\sigma)\left[\begin{matrix}E_{x}\\
E_{y}\\
E_{z}
\end{matrix}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stretched-coordinate expression yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{matrix}\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial y}-\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial H_{y}}{\partial z}\\
\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial H_{x}}{\partial z}-\frac{1}{s_{x}}\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial x}\\
\frac{1}{s_{x}}\frac{\partial H_{y}}{\partial x}-\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial H_{x}}{\partial y}
\end{matrix}\right]=(i\omega\epsilon_{0})\left[\begin{matrix}E_{x}\\
E_{y}\\
E_{z}
\end{matrix}\right]\label{Ampere's law in freq domain, CPML}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{n}=1+\frac{\sigma_{n}}{i\omega\epsilon}\hfill where\;n=x,\:y,\:z
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Complex-frequency-shifted (CFL-PML) formulation, more general stretched
 coordinate is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{n}=\kappa_{n}+\frac{\sigma_{n}}{\alpha_{n}+i\omega\epsilon}\hfill where\;i=x,\:y,\:z
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then Ampere's law in time-domain becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overrightarrow{\nabla}\times\overrightarrow{\mathscr{H}}=\frac{\partial\overrightarrow{\mathscr{D}}}{\partial t}+\overrightarrow{\mathscr{J}}=\epsilon\frac{\partial\overrightarrow{\mathscr{E}}}{\partial t}+\sigma\overrightarrow{\mathscr{E}}\label{Ampere's law}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{matrix}\overline{s_{y}}\ast\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}-\overline{s_{z}}\ast\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial z}\\
\overline{s_{z}}\ast\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial z}-\overline{s_{x}}\ast\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial x}\\
\overline{s_{z}}\ast\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{y}}{\partial x}-\overline{s_{y}}\ast\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{x}}{\partial y}
\end{matrix}\right]=(\epsilon_{0}\frac{\partial}{\partial t})\left[\begin{matrix}\mathscr{E}_{x}\\
\mathscr{E}_{y}\\
\mathscr{E}_{z}
\end{matrix}\right]\label{Ampere's law in CPML method}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{s_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, before we proceed, let's check the convolution theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of convolution is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f\ast g)(t)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(\tau)g(t-\tau)d\tau
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interesting property of convolution, which called convolution theorem
 is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathscr{F}\left\{ f\ast g\right\} =\mathscr{F}\left\{ f\right\} \cdot\mathscr{F}\left\{ g\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{F}$
\end_inset

 denotes Fourier transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ampere's law in freq domain, CPML"

\end_inset

, the x component is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial y}-\frac{1}{s_{z}}\frac{\partial H_{y}}{\partial z}=(i\omega\epsilon+\sigma)E_{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term on left side can be interpreted as the product of two Fourier
 transformed function f and g.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathscr{F}\left\{ f\right\} \cdot\mathscr{F}\left\{ g\right\} =\frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial y}=\mathscr{F}\left\{ f\ast g\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\ast g=\mathscr{F}^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s_{y}}\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial y}\right\} =\overline{s_{y}}\ast\frac{\partial\mathscr{H}_{z}}{\partial y}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{s_{y}}=\mathscr{F}^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s_{y}}\right\} =\mathscr{F}^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{\kappa_{y}+\frac{\sigma_{y}}{\alpha_{y}+i\omega\epsilon}}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Fourier transform theory yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{s_{n}}=\mathscr{F}^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{\kappa_{n}+\frac{\sigma_{n}}{\alpha_{n}+i\omega\epsilon}}\right)=\frac{\delta(t)}{\kappa_{n}}-\frac{\sigma_{n}}{\epsilon_{0}\kappa_{n}^{2}}e^{-\left(\frac{\sigma_{n}}{\epsilon\kappa_{n}}+\frac{\alpha_{n}}{\epsilon}\right)t}u(t)=\frac{\delta(t)}{\kappa_{n}}+\zeta_{n}(t)\label{zeta from inv F.T.}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
